“## Kikuchi Patternn”, “n”, “An electron can be scattered elastically into the Bragg angle, or it can be scattered inelasticallyn”, “n”, “The inelastically scattered electrons are emitted in all directions.n”, “n”, “These inelastically scattered electrons are then diffracted at the crystal planes according to Bragg’s law. n”, “n”, “n”, “![Kossel cone](images/Kikuchi-small.png)n”, “n”, “This results in a cone, where the Bragg diffraction is allowed; this cone is called Kossel cone. Because the electrons are predominantly scattered in the direction of the incident beam, this Bragg diffraction will take some intensity out of the original beam (dark line: deficit line in the figure )and transfer it to a different angle (bright band: excess line in the figure. Inside this bands is some intensity which depends on the dynamic scattering.”

]

}, {

“cell_type”: “markdown”, “metadata”: {}, “source”: [

“The most important feature of the Kikuchi band is that the Kossel cones are fixed to the crystal and allow easy navigation in reciprocal space, because nothing changes with the angle (the excitation error and thickness changes for SAD patterns). n”, “A common example if you want to tilt out of a zone axis, but you also want to keep an interface edge on; you just follow the Kikuchi band of the interface plane.n”, “n”, “Note: n”, “>the Kikuchi bands are bent, they just appear straight, because the Ewald sphere is so large. n”, “n”, “Note: n”, “>According to the explanation above, no Kikuchi lines should be visible if we are in a low order zone axis. This is not true because of the channeling effect and dynamic scattering, but these effects do not change anything about the location, where we expect the Kikuchi lines.”

]

“## Kikuchi Line Constructionn”, “The Kikuchi lines are the Bisections of lines from the center spot to the Bragg spots.n”, “n”, “The line equation for a bisection of a line between two points $(A(x_A,y_A), B(x_B,y_B))$ is given by the formula:n”, “n”, “$y=-\frac{x_A-x_B}{y_A-y_B}x+\frac{x_A^2-x_B^2+y_A^2-y_B^2}{2 \cdot(y_A-y_B)}$n”, “n”, “If $y_A = y_B$, then x is constant at $x= \frac{1}{2} (x_A+x_B)$n”, “n”, “In our case point $B$ is $(0,0)$ and so above equation is:n”, “n”, “$y=-\frac{x_A}{y_A}x+\frac{x_A^2+y_A^2}{2 y_A}$ n”, “n”, “If $y_A$ is zero, the line is horizontal and $ x$ is constant at $x= \frac{1}{2} x_A$.”

“Assume we have an SAD pattern, from experiment or simulation. Draw a line from the center to each ZOLZ diffraction spot and draw a line perpendicular to the first line at half the distance. We name the line with the same Miller indices as the spot. The distance between two pair of lines is then again $|\vec{g}|$ of the original spots. n”, “n”, “If we know in which direction the next low order zone axis is and how far we have to tilt to get to it, we can draw that pole too.”
